Dec 10 2004	Good value... but tiny rooms!!	We stayed three nights at the Vancouver Studios. The hotel is centrally located near lots of restaurants and just a short walk to Bayswater &amp; Queensway tube stations. We booked a double room with private bath for 75 pounds per night. It was truly a good value for London. However, the room was extremely small. There is no room for storage and barely any room to move around! Often, I felt claustrophobic inside the room!! Our room was on the fourth floor and there was no lift. We had to carry our luggage up extremly narrow stairways- there are no bellmen to help. Although my boyfriend and I are both young and in good shape... walking up those stairs a few times a day proved to be tedious and annoying, especially after shopping or a night out drinking at the pubs. If you have any physical limitations or handicaps, I would not recommend this hotel. Overall, our room was extremely clean and the staff was friendly. Oh, and our shower had great pressure!! I would recommend for the location, cleanliness, and price.. but just don't expect too much.	
Dec 4 2004	Very cozy and homey	Just returned a few days ago from London, having stayed at the Vancouver Studios for 7 nites and enjoyed it so very much. We were very pleased with the room, although of course very small but typical of Europe unless you are REALLY spending big bucks. However was totally impressed with how cozy it was, extremely clean, the beds and bedding were WONDERFUL, shower was great, water pressure was almost extreme until you got used to it. We had room #14 which was above the garden area and even in late November, it was a pleasure to look out at it. The kitchenette was very adequate and everything was quite new. And being pet lovers, we very much enjoyed the companionship in the evening in the room off the garden with the sofas, reading material, fireplace glowing and Panther, the resident cat on the arm of the sofa. Very much like home and would highly recommend it to anyone. And have always enjoyed the Bayswater area, handy and so ethnic. Very enjoyable. Mary Jayne Hallifax and daughters from Michigan	
Nov 30 2004	Climbing Mount Vancouver	Stayed 4 nights at the Vancouver Studios, November 25 - 29, 2004. The location of the hotel is a real plus. Just steps away from the Whiteley's Shopping Centre, Queensway, and an easy walk to Notting Hill and the Portobello Road area. Great public transportation links and almost always easy to get a taxi. The staff was friend and the decor of the hotel was better than most other places I have stayed at in this price range. I will echo other reviewers comments about the kitchen. It really isn't useable as a real kitchen. We had a small microwave with a tempermental timer, a refrigerator, an electric kettle and a two-burner cook top. Very limited pots/pans and dishes. But, it was a treat to have a fridge and made getting sandwiches or sausage rolls for a late-night snack an option, as well as a cold beverage when you wanted one. The biggest drawback is the hotel's lack on an elevator (lift). We were on the 4th floor and we counted 96 steps to the top of &quot;Mount Vancouver&quot; as we began to call it. I was glad I packed small bags but I can't imagine anyone who has any kind of mobility (or vertigo) wanting to stay on the 4th floor. The bathroom shower stall was very small. (Of course, I am a healthy 250 lbs, so I had more of an issue than my wife). On the plus side, the shower had the best water pressure and tempature control I have ever had in a London hotel. It took a minute to figure it out (one knob is temperature, the other is pressure) but once that was sorted out it was fine.  We had a good sized closet with plenty of hangers provided. The TV was a disappointment, offering only the standard 5 BBC/ITV channels (and our remote didn't work). As others have commented, there is no alarm clock or radio provided. The hotel doesn't gouge you on telephone charges, direct-dial local calls are charged at 20p - useful for making restaurant reservations. The double bed was the size of an american &quot;full&quot; and took a bit getting used to from having a queen-sized at home. In all, it was a good value. It isn't the nicest place I've ever stayed in London, but it certainly is good for the neighborhood.	
